\frame{
\frametitle{Money}
Different definitions:
\begin{itemize}
\item liquid (=easy to use, 0 interest) asset
\item narrow definition: cash, checking deposits, and debit card 
\item broad definition: narrow+deposits of currency
\item other financial assets are illiquid
\end{itemize}
}

\frame{
\frametitle{Money Supply \& Demand}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{money supply} is controlled by the Central Bank 
\item \textbf{money demand} represents the amount of monetary assets that people are willing to hold. This is based on:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Interest rates/expected rates of return 
\item Risk/inflation
\item Liquidity
\end{enumerate}
\end{itemize}
}


\Section{Chapter 14. A Model of the  Money Market }
\frame{
\frametitle{Aggregate Demand of Real Money}
The aggregate demand of real money can be expressed as:
\begin{center}
$\frac{M^{d}}{P} =L\left(R,Y\right)$
\end{center}
where:
\begin{itemize}
\item $P$ is the price level
\item $Y$ is real national income
\item $R$ is a measure of interest rates on non-monetary assets
\item $L\left(R,Y\right)$ is the aggregate demand of real monetary assets
\end{itemize}
}

\frame[plain]{
\frametitle{Fig. 14-2: Effect on the Aggregate Real Money Demand Schedule of a Rise in Real Income}
\begin{figure}
	\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{due.pdf}
	\label{fig:11}
\end{figure}
}


\frame{
\frametitle{A Model of the Money Market}
In equilibrium:
\begin{center}
$M^{s}=M^{d}$
\end{center}
or
\begin{center}
$\frac{M^{s}}{P} =L\left(R,Y\right)$
\end{center}
If is an excess supply of monetary assets $\Rightarrow$ excess demand for interest bearing assets like bonds, loans, and deposits.
}


