\frame{
\frametitle{Changes in the Domestic Money Supply}
An increase in a country's money supply:
\begin{itemize}
\item $R \Downarrow$
\item depreciation of the domestic currency
\end{itemize}
An increase in a country's money supply:
\begin{itemize}
\item $R \Uparrow$
\item appreciation of the domestic currency
\end{itemize}
}


\frame{
\frametitle{Changes in the Foreign Money Supply}
How would a change in the supply of euros  affect the U.S. money market and foreign exchange markets?
\begin{itemize}
\item An increase in the supply of euros $\Rightarrow$ depreciation of the euro
\begin{enumerate}
\item $R\ EURO \Downarrow$
\item depreciation of the euro
\end{enumerate}
\item A decrease in the supply of euros $\Rightarrow$ appreciation of the euro
\end{itemize}
}


\frame[plain]{
\frametitle{Fig 14-9: Effect of an Increase in the European Money Supply on the Dollar/Euro Exchange Rate}
\begin{figure}
	\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{dieci.pdf}
	\label{fig:11}
\end{figure}
}

\Section{Chapter 14. Long \& Short Run}

\frame{
\frametitle{Long \& Short Run}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Short run:} prices are sticky
\item \textbf{Long run:} prices of factors of production (wages, real interest rate) and of output have sufficient time to adjust to market conditions.
\end{itemize}
}


\frame{
\frametitle{In the Long Run}
In the long run, there is a direct relationship between the inflation rate and changes in the money supply.
\begin{itemize}
\item $M^{s} = P x L\left(R,Y\right)$
\item $P =\frac{M^{s}}{L\left(R,Y\right)}$
\item $\frac{\Delta P}{P} = \frac{\Delta M^{s}}{M^{s}} - \frac{\Delta L}{L}$
\end{itemize}
The inflation rate is predicted to equal the growth rate in money supply minus the growth rate in money demand.
}


\frame[plain]{
\frametitle{Fig 14-10: Average Money Growth and Inflation in Western Hemisphere Developing Countries, by Year, 1987-–2006}
\begin{figure}
	\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{corre.pdf}
	\label{fig:11}
\end{figure}
}

\frame{
\frametitle{Money and Prices in the Long Run }
How does a positive change in the money supply cause prices of output and inputs to change?
\begin{enumerate}
\item Excess demand of goods and services: labor $\Uparrow$ $\Rightarrow$ wage $w \Uparrow$  $ P \Uparrow$
\item Inflationary expectations: $P^{e} \Uparrow w \Uparrow P \Uparrow$
\end{enumerate}
}

\frame[plain]{
\frametitle{Money, Prices, Exchange Rates, and Expectations (1)}
\begin{figure}
	\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.90\textwidth]{ex1.pdf}
	\label{fig:11}
\end{figure}
}

\frame[plain]{
\frametitle{Money, Prices, Exchange Rates, and Expectations (2)}
\begin{figure}
	\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.90\textwidth]{ex2.pdf}
	\label{fig:11}
\end{figure}
}


\frame{
\frametitle{Money, Prices, Exchange Rates, and Expectations (3)}
\begin{enumerate}
\item A permanent increase in a country's money supply causes a proportional long run depreciation of its currency.
\item A permanent decrease in a country's money supply causes a proportional long run appreciation of its currency.
\end{enumerate}
}


\frame[plain]{
\frametitle{Money, Prices, Exchange Rates, and Expectations (4)}
\begin{figure}
	\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.90\textwidth]{ex3.pdf}
	\label{fig:11}
\end{figure}
}


\frame{
\frametitle{Exchange Rate Overshooting}
\begin{itemize}
\item The exchange rate is said to overshoot when its immediate response to a change is greater than its long run response.
\item Overshooting is predicted to occur when monetary policy has an immediate effect on interest rates, but not on prices and (expected) inflation.
\item Overshooting helps explain why exchange rates are so volatile
\end{itemize}
}

\frame[plain]{
\frametitle{Fig 14-11: Month-to-Month Variability of the Dollar/Yen Exchange Rate and of the U.S./Japan Price Level Ratio, 1974$-$–2007}
\begin{figure}
	\centering
